					<li>
						<a href="#" class="accordeon-trigger">
							<span class="accordeon-plus">+</span><span class="accordeon-minus is-display-none">-</span>Exhibitions in the Library						</a>
						<div class="accordeon-content">
							<div class="text-block">
								<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h4 style="text-align: left;" align="CENTER"><strong>Celebrating VanDusen in Painting:<br />
</strong>Vancouver en Plein Air Painting Group</h4>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span lang="en-CA"><a href="http://www.vandusengarden.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/plein-air.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-1733"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1733" src="http://www.vandusengarden.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/plein-air.jpg" alt="plein air" width="820" height="591" /></a></span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span lang="en-CA"><span lang="en-CA">Watercolour by Hans Gray, Vancouver </span><span lang="en-CA">en plein air</span><span lang="en-CA"> group</span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span lang="en-CA">The </span><span lang="en-CA">Vancouver </span><span lang="en-CA">en plein air</span><span lang="en-CA"> group was formed in 2011 when we first gathered in Stanley Park to paint on April 18</span><span lang="en-CA">th</span><span lang="en-CA"> of that year. Our love of outdoor painting, the joy of companionship, and the exchange of ideas has kept us together every week despite the often inclement weather. VanDusen Garden has, of course, been one of our favorite spots to paint during all seasons. In this garden we find a worldliness, an enchantment, a repetition of colours, a variety of textures, a myriad of forms to paint, and we do so in unique peacefulness. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span lang="en-CA">This exhibition of the works of 13 painters is a small sample reflecting different visions and expressions of “place.” VanDusen is a “place” that has moved each one of us in different ways, and one that we discover anew each week, all year long. You will see images in watercolour, acrylic and oil </span><span lang="en-CA">medium </span>inspired by such places as: <span lang="en-CA">Autumn</span><span lang="en-CA"> Stroll, Black Garden, Rose Garden, Heron Lake, and rhododendron areas, as well as other views. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span lang="en-CA">The painters’ different artistic backgrounds and life journeys are compiled in an album with small biographies, images and contact information. This album is available for viewing in the library.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><span lang="en-CA">This exhibition will run April/May/June 2016, and all art works are for sale.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: left;" align="CENTER"><span lang="en-CA">We welcome you to our </span><span lang="en-CA">Exhibit</span> <span lang="en-CA">Opening </span><span style="line-height: 1.5;">on Saturday, April 9th, 2016 from 2:00 to 4:00 p.m.</span></p>
							</div>
													</div>
					</li>
	
				
		</ul>
	</div>
</div>
<div class="layout-wrapper">
	<div id="" class="layout-wrapper layout-wrapper-smaller is-no-padding-right">
		<ul class="accordeon">
	
				
					<li>
						<a href="#" class="accordeon-trigger">
							<span class="accordeon-plus">+</span><span class="accordeon-minus is-display-none">-</span>New in the library						</a>
						<div class="accordeon-content">
							<div class="text-block">
								<p><strong>Living life in full bloom : 120 daily practices to deepen your passion, creativity and relationships</strong><br />
by <em>Murray, Elizabeth</em><br />
Call #: BF637 .S4 M874 2014<br />
1 copy circ.</p>
<p>With Elizabeth Murray‘s wise guide to ‘Living Life in Full Bloom’ you can create your own plan for the future by identifying your own set of unique four pathways to follow.</p>
<p><img class="alignnone wp-image-849 size-full" src="/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/8B0NA0bsY1WnsAAAAASUVORK5CYII.png" alt="8B0NA0bsY1WnsAAAAASUVORK5CYII=" width="135" height="138" /></p>
<p><strong>Among the islands : [adventures in the Pacific]</strong><br />
by <em>Flannery, Tim F. </em><br />
Call #: CT9971 .F53 A3 2012<br />
1 copy circ.</p>
<p>Twenty-five years ago, a young curator of mammals from the Australian Museum in Sydney set out to research the fauna of the Pacific Islands. With accounts of discovering, naming and sometimes eating new mammal species; being thwarted or aided by local customs; and historic scientific expeditions, Tim Flannery takes us on an enthralling journey.</p>
<p><img class="alignnone wp-image-851 size-full" src="/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Bf72yd8AAAAASUVORK5CYII.png" alt="Bf72yd8AAAAASUVORK5CYII=" width="106" height="159" /></p>
<p><strong>Cooked : a natural history of transformation</strong><br />
by <em>Pollan, Michael</em><br />
Call #: GT2850 .P656 2013<br />
1 copy circ.</p>
<p>Pollan explores the previously uncharted territory of his own kitchen. Here, he discovers the enduring power of the four classical elements&#8211;fire, water, air, and earth&#8211;to transform the stuff of nature into delicious things to eat and drink. In the course of his journey, he discovers that the cook occupies a special place in the world, standing squarely between nature and culture. Both realms are transformed by cooking, and so, in the process, is the cook.</p>
<p><img class="alignnone wp-image-850 size-full" src="/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/JyuBAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC.png" alt="JyuBAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC" width="102" height="155" /></p>
<p><strong>Practical botany for gardeners : over 3,000 botanical terms explained and explored</strong></p>
<p>by <em>Hodge, Geoff</em><br />
Call #: QK50 .H63 2013<br />
1 copy circ.</p>
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td width="100%">Provides easy-to-understand explanations of over 3,000 botanical words and terms, and shows how these can be applied to everyday gardening practice.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><img class="alignnone wp-image-852 size-full" src="/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/vI-IP22A3AG8T-Uql5BiMAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC.png" alt="+vI+IP22A3AG8T+Uql5BiMAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC" width="149" height="200" /></p>
<p><strong>The story of Kew Gardens in photographs</strong><br />
by <em>Parker, Lynn</em><br />
Call #: QK73 .G72 P47 2013<br />
1 copy circ.</p>
<p>This splendidly illustrated book about the world famous botanic gardens at Kew examines their historic impact and importance. With 250 fascinating photographs, many of them previously unseen, it describes the botanical, social, cultural, political and technological developments of the past two centuries and highlights the pivotal role that plants have played in British life. The tale of Kew Gardens embraces a wide range of themes, including: plant hunters, ecologists, explorers and other pioneers; the evolution of building and garden design; influential directors, architects and landscape gardeners; the gardens as a vital public resource; digging for victory &#8211; Kew in wartime.</p>
<p><img class="alignnone wp-image-853 size-full" src="/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/B4rkidGwZ07HAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC.png" alt="B4rkidGwZ07HAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC" width="169" height="120" /></p>
<p><strong>Herbs for healthy aging : natural prescriptions for vibrant health</strong><br />
by <em>Hoffmann, David</em><br />
Call #: RM666 .H33 H62 2014<br />
1 copy circ.</p>
<p>In this herbal guide to healthy aging, medical herbalist David Hoffmann discusses how to maintain the body&#8217;s vitality as we age and how to treat and prevent the health concerns brought about by aging.</p>
<p><img class="alignnone wp-image-848 size-full" src="/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/AQR6HkgK9oCuAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC.png" alt="AQR6HkgK9oCuAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC" width="133" height="200" /></p>
							</div>
													</div>
					</li>
	
				
